05697nam a22009135i 9781575068657DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20212013pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815750686577 a10.1515/97815750686572doi  a(DE-B1597)583897  a(OCoLC)1253313774  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBL1060b.C74 2013eb 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04a202/.422300aCreation and Chaos :bA Reconsideration of Hermann Gunkel's Chaoskampf Hypothesis /ced. by Richard H. Beal, JoAnn Scurlock. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHermann Gunkel was a scholar in the generation of the origins of Assyriology, the spectacular discovery by George Smith of fragments of the "Chaldean Genesis," and the Babel-Bibel debate. Gunkel's thesis, inspired by materials supplied to him by the Assyriologist Heinrich Zimmern, was to take the Chaoskampf motif of Revelation as an event that would not only occur at the end of the world but had already happened at the beginning, before Creation. In other words, in this theory, one imagines God in Genesis 1 as first having battled Rahab, Leviathan, and Yam (the forces of Chaos) in a grand battle, and only then beginning to create.The problem with Gunkel's theory is that it did not simply identify common elements in the mythologies of the ancient Near East but imposed upon them a structure dictating the relationships between the elements, a structure that was based on inadequate knowledge and a forced interpretation of his sources. On the other hand, one is not entitled to insist that there was no cultural conversation among peoples who spent the better part of several millennia trading with, fighting, and conquering one another.Creation and Chaos attempts to address some of these issues. The contributions are organized into five sections that address various aspects of the issues raised by Gunekl's theories.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aCreationxMythologyxMiddle East. 0aCreationxMythologyzMiddle East. 0aMonstersxMiddle East. 0aMonsterszMiddle East. 0aMythology, Middle Eastern. 0aReligion and politicsxHistoryxTo 1500xMiddle EastxMiddle East. 0aReligion and politicszMiddle EastxHistoryyTo 1500. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aAverbeck, Richard E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBatto, Bernard F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeal, Richard H., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBenz, Brendon C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, Dennis R. M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeinman, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrayne, Douglas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilan, Amir, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLambert, W. G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLundström, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMelvin, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller Ii, Robert D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPitard, Wayne T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScurlock, JoAnn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScurlock, JoAnn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSonik, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct